For the code:

```js
/**
 * @example
 * ```
 * render () {
 *     return (
 *         <div className='NameField'>{this.l('NAME_FIELD')}</div>
 *     );
 * }
 * ```
 */
function getDocument() {
    return '';
}
```

Hover currently displays:

![screen shot 2017-05-10 at 2 38 42 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/12821956/25922555/816fbcbe-358e-11e7-8cf6-440cb6b5e8c2.png)

In this case the code block in `@example` is not correctly shown

When I'm editing JSON files, VSCode suggests to add the `$schema` key:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/101152/25917874/cddf7dc4-35c9-11e7-9333-4152bc379e44.png)

It is also mentioned [in the documentation](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-docs/blame/fc67325512852881253186ab3f8745b2a842d423/docs/languages/json.md#L63) in the ["Mapping in the JSON" section](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/languages/json#_mapping-in-the-json).

However, according to JSON Schema specification [section 7](http://json-schema.org/latest/json-schema-core.html#rfc.section.7), the `$schema` keyword is only intended to be used in schemas themselves. So VSCode's usage is non-standard.

I'm new to schemas and the non-standard behavior caused some confusion. For example, I wanted to describe a JSON which is an object of objects:

```json
{
    "some": {},
    "json": {}
}
```

so I created this schema:

```json
{
  "type": "object",
  "patternProperties": {
    ".+": {
      "type": "object"
    }
  }
}
```

and mapped it using the `$schema` keyword in the JSON file [according to the docs](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/languages/json#_mapping-in-the-json) but it yields this error:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/101152/25918234/02e837d0-35cb-11e7-93b0-f71e57f0a4a4.png)

If I map it using any other method, e.g., settings.json, all works fine:

```
{
    "json.schemas": [
        {
            "fileMatch": [
                "example.json"
            ],
            "url": "./example.schema.json"
        }
    ]
}
```

I don't know the historic background but the simplest "fix" would be to remove the non-standard in-JSON mapping method ~~although to be entirely honest, I am more surprised that `$schema` inside JSON isn't supported by the JSON Schema standard; it seems quite logical to me~~ UPDATE: see comment below.
